# Binary streaming via binary-ref chunks

**Status: Implemented** — `de1c6fb`, `a1899ca`

All prerequisites are implemented:
- [`SubscribeFiltered`](./subscribe-filters)
- [`Connection IDs`](./connection-ids)
- [`Direct-to`](./direct-to)
- [`Mutations`](./mutations)

Binary-store connects via `subscribe_filtered` for `BinaryRef` chunks only — no `SubscribeAll`.

## ContentType::BinaryRef

New variant on `Chunk`:

```rust
pub enum ContentType {
    Text,
    Binary,
    BinaryRef,
    Null,
}
```

A `BinaryRef` chunk announces a binary asset with metadata but no data:

```rust
Chunk {
    id: "uuid",
    content_type: BinaryRef,
    content: None,
    data: None,
    mime_type: Some("audio/wav"),
    annotations: { ... },
    producer: "com.nominal.cafe-tts",
    timestamp: ...,
}
```

## SSE unification

`serialize_chunk` in `cafe-server/src/binary_ref.rs` produces the same JSON shape from three paths:

```rust
pub fn serialize_chunk(chunk: &Chunk, binary_refs: bool) -> Value {
    let use_ref = (binary_refs && chunk.content_type == ContentType::Binary)
               || chunk.content_type == ContentType::BinaryRef;

    if use_ref {
        json!({
            "id":           chunk.id,
            "content_type": "binary-ref",
            "content": {
                "chunk_id":  chunk.id,
                "mime_type": chunk.mime_type,   // asset mime (inside content)
            },
            "data":         null,                // never inline base64 in ref mode
            "mime_type":    null,                // top-level always null; use content.mime_type
            "producer":     chunk.producer,
            "annotations":  chunk.annotations,
            "timestamp":    chunk.timestamp,
        })
    } else {
        serde_json::to_value(chunk).unwrap_or(Value::Null)
    }
}
```

`byte_size` is optional — included in `content` as a separate annotation key when known (see below).

## byte_size

Optional annotation on `BinaryRef` chunks (`binary.byte_size: u64`). Include it if known (e.g., TTS knows duration × bitrate). Omit for streaming scenarios where total size isn't known upfront.

For old-style `Binary` chunks serialized with `?binaryRefs=1`, `byte_size` is inferred from `data.len()` and included in the SSE output as `content.byte_size`. No data loss.

